04169nam a22005775i 9780889209404DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892094047 a10.51644/97808892094042doi  a(DE-B1597)667409  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1054.5 .S55 P43 2006 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a971.4a971.4660009200aLove Strong as Death :bLucy Peel’s Canadian Journal, 1833-1836 /ced. by J.I. Little. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (239 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Childhood and Family in Canada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tFrequently Mentioned Names -- tBook One -- tBook Two -- tBook Three -- tNotes -- tIndex to Letters0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA transcription of Lucy Peel’s wonderfully readable journal was recently discovered in her descendent’s house in Norwich, England. Sent in regular installments to her transatlantic relatives, the journal presents an intimate narrative of Lucy’s Canadian sojourn with her husband, Edmund Peel, an officer on leave from the British navy. Her daily entries begin with their departure as a young, newlywed couple from the shores of England in 1833 and end with their decision to return to the comforts of home after three and a half years of hard work as pioneer settlers. Lucy Peel’s evocative diary focuses on the semi-public world of family and community in Lower Canada’s Eastern Townships, and fulfils the same role as Susanna Moodie’s writings had for the Upper Canadian frontier. Though their perspective was from a small, privileged sector of society, these genteel women writers were sharp observers of their social and natural surroundings, and they provide valuable insights into the ideology and behaviour of the social class that dominated the Canadian colonies during the pre-Rebellion era. Women’s voices are rarely heard in the official records that comprise much of the historical archives. Lucy Peel’s intensely romantic journal reveals how crucially important domesticity was to the local British officials. Lucy Peel’s diary, like those of such counterparts as Catherine Parr Traill, also suggests that genteel women were better prepared for their role in the New World than Canadian historians have generally assumed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezQuébec (Province)zSherbrooke Region. 0aPioneerszQuébec (Province)zSherbrooke RegionvDiaries. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aLittle, J.I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920940440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209404/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles